recordings.rmk:
A Mt. Washington Park Ranger indicated this location for possible Bicknell's Thrush.

I made several stops along this Dolly Copp/Pinkham Road which is hotspot named : White Mt. National  Forest--Dolly Copp/Pinkham B Road , Coos County, New Hampshire, US.

Area was an older secondary growth with mixture of pine and deciduous trees.

Windy with leaf noise heard throughout.

Playback of Bicknell's Song used and at third stop at which I was moving higher in elevation along road, an unseen bird vocalized, heard and recorded. 

The sound I am trying to ID is heard  is  three /four notes ending in a higher trill and starts just before 5 second mark of recording and heard 5 times in recording.

There is another bird vocalization in recording on the 1st and 3rd time of  focal point bird's vocalization, which I think is a warbler, Am. Redstart.

Audacity was used to edit recording.  Normalized Max. Amplitude at -3dB.

recordings.loc: Burrillville, Providence County, Rhode Island
recordings.rmk: Canon EOS Rebel T3i built-in mic. Habitat: Mixed deciduous forest. Behavior: Singing perhaps once every 20 seconds. Conditions: Sunny, 80 degrees F, strong wind which was filtered out of recording. This bird is actually one male of maybe 6 or 7 pairs in this part of the state that breeds here, despite what the xc range map says. Also a few in nearby Douglas SF in Massachusetts.
